  "title": "Imaginative Test Run",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b30daf539f5ff2f2",
      "text": "However, one has to distinguish: first to conceive a plan, second to develop it, third to execute it. Thus there are two ways to my >preconceived anticipation to make it explicit: an inner-imaginative and an outer-active one. >Cautious< as I am, I develop my intention first in imagination; only then I carry out the \"foreseen < actions also in reality. The whole way, which is contained folded in my intention, is unfolded on a trial basis, played through imaginatively, in order to be actually gone only afterwards.\nAnd so I go my way in thoughts: nicely one after the other, but nevertheless summarized; not step by step, but concentrated on striking points and critical places like beginnings and obstacles, cuts and turning points. I also know that what I have planned to do will not simply coincide with what will then really take place; it is always two different things: what I intend to do and what I have in front of me. Therefore, the imaginative rehearsal is always a question-and-answer game. I anticipate what I am going to do, not without the external conditions under which my doing will probably have to take place. I fantasize situations and how I will master them, problems and how I will solve them. I imagine both: a variety of factual conditions as they might be, and myself as I would act in each situation to get closer to my goal.\nAnd such are the questions that must occupy me there: How do I get there? How, if I am there, do I know that I am there? How do I find my way back? How much time and strength do I need? What will happen to me on the way? What coincidences could distract me, what incidents could get to me, what accidents could set me back? Which barriers could stop me, which cliffs could make me fail? And what is the probability of each of these?\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "da8ffd435fb22aed",
      "text": "⇒ [[Consider the Means]]"
    }
